One  of  the  significant  challenges  to  treat  tuberculosis  is  the  phenotypic  resistance  adapted  by  the  latent or dormant Mycobacterium tuberculosis (M. tuberculosis) cells against most of the available  drugs. Different in-vitro assay such as oxygen depletion model and nutrient starvation models have  contributed  to  unravelling  the  pathogen  phenotypic  resistance  but  are  too  cumbersome  for  streptomycin-starved  18b  (SS18b)  mutant  strain  of  M.  tuberculosis  provided  a  simple  and  reproducible  model.  This  model  mimics  latent  tuberculosis  and  is  best  suited  for  screening  medicinally  appropriate  libraries.  Using  SS18b  strain  in  a  resazurin  reduction  microplate  assay  (REMA), high-throughput screening of ChemDiv library constituting of 30,000 compounds resulted  in  the  identification  of  470  active  compounds.  Clustering  and  scaffolding  based  medicinal  chemistry  analysis  characterized  these  hits  into  15  scaffolds.  Seven  most  potent  compounds

exhibiting  an  MIC  <  1µg/ml  against  SS18b  were  non-toxic  in  HepG2  cell  line  (selective  Index  ≥  160). Our screening revealed seven novel compounds exhibiting activity against the non-replicating  form of M tuberculosis. 8002-7516 was the most promising compound showing intracellular killing  and could be optimized to develop a lead drug candidate. According to the global tuberculosis report 2018 by World Health Organization (WHO) an  estimated  1.3  million  deaths  were  caused  by  TB  alone,  with  an  additional  300,  000  deaths  in  association  with  HIV  in  2017.  Globally,  10.0  million  people  developed  TB  disease  in  2017,   558,000  people  developed  TB  resistant  to  the  most  effective  first-line  anti-tuberculosis  drug,  rifampicin  (RR-TB),  where  82%  of  the  population  had  multidrug-resistant  TB  (MDR-TB)  in  the  •  Screening  of  30,000  chemDiv  library  identified  seven  novel  compounds  having  activity  •  All compounds were non-toxic on HepG2 cell line. Tuberculosis is one of the top 10 causes of death and the leading cause of a single infectious  to  high-throughput  screening  (HTS)  assays.  In  this  context,  non-replicating  year 2017. China accounts for almost half of the world's population cases of MDR/RR-TB (13%),  India (24%), and the Russian Federation (10%) alone [1].

directly observed therapy short-course (DOTS) involving a combination of four drugs (rifampicin,  isoniazid, pyrazinamide, and ethambutol)  for treating TB  is required for two months, followed by  rifampin and isoniazid for a period of 4 months [2]. The crisis is further convoluted by multidrug- resistant  MDR  and  extensively  drug-resistant  XDR-TB  strains  that  have  become  resistant  to  common  antibiotics  due  to  poor  adherence  to  such  a  lengthy  treatment  [3,  4].  Several  drug  discovery programs have initiated worldwide, aiming to find therapeutic agents to overcome such  phenotypic  resistant  pathogens  [5]  either  by  replacing  or  complementing  already  existing  DOTS.  Once the pathogen encounters the host, it has to cope with the ability of the pathogen to enter the  latent  phase  [6,  7].  An  estimated  1.7  billion  people  that  contribute  23%  of  the  world  population  have latent TB infection are thus at the risk of developing active TB disease during their lifetime.   [8, 9]. The pathogen encounters various stresses inside the host; these stresses have been mimicked  in vitro by different models, like, the oxygen depletion model and nutrient starvation model. Nitric  oxide  treatment  and  acidic  medium  represent  two  additional  stresses  that  M.  tuberculosis  has  to  counter  during  infection.  Such  models  either  alone  or  in  combination  [10-15]  have  contributed  to  unravelling the pathogen phenotypic resistance, or so there role cannot be neglected. Still, they are  too tedious for application to HTS assays. Hence, a candidate that is simple, reproducible, and easy  to mimic in-vitro, as well as in-vivo conditions,  was required.  In this context, SS18b was used to  mimic  dormant  bacteria.  This  strain  was  isolated  in  Japan  in  1955  from  a  patient  diagnosed  with

streptomycin-resistant tuberculosis. The phenotype is recognized as streptomycin dependent, as the  microorganism was unable to  grow in  absence of streptomycin. Additionally, when maintained in  streptomycin  media,  it  did  not  lose  viability  for  several  weeks  and  grew  again  upon  addition  of  streptomycin [16]. Molecular characterization revealed novel mutation in rrs gene that encodes for  16S rRNA to be responsible for a streptomycin-dependent mutant of Mycobacterium tuberculosis.  Insertion  of  an  additional  cytosine  in  the  530  loop  region  of  16S  rRNA  may  have  streptomycin  dependence. The presence of streptomycin presumably stabilizes the interaction in a way that leads  to normal functioning of the ribosome in such strain [17]. In the present study, ChemDiv library of  30,000  drugs  like  compounds  procured  from  ChemDiv  library  was  screened  to  find  new  lead  compounds using HTS assay against non-replicating SS18b strain of M. tuberculosis. Compounds  with promising MICs were further investigated.   From the past four decades, the therapy to treat TB has remained unchanged. Discovery  Informatics  department  of  CSIR-Indian Institute of Integrative Medicine developed filtering criteria based on Lipinski's rule to  prune the compounds to a reasonable number. Filters such as Molecules with Molecular Weight of  compounds < 400, without undesirable reactive groups and "suspicious" chemotypes other than H,  C, N, O, F, S, P, Cl, Br, I, with ADME properties similar to FDA approved 1712 drugs and CLogP  value between 1.5 & 5 were used for screening. Also, Physico-chemical drug-likeness and structural  lead-likeness properties were considered to find compounds with desirable properties.   2.3. In vitro generation of growth of non-replicating SS18b   described  by  C.  Sala  2010  [18].  Briefly,  the  culture  was  grown  in  Middlebrook  7H9  broth  supplemented with 10% ADC and 50 μg/ml streptomycin at 37 °C in 5% CO2 till it reached mid-log  phase. Cell pellet obtained after centrifugation was washed three times with phosphate buffer saline  (pH 7.4) to remove leftover streptomycin. The culture was then re-suspended in streptomycin free  Middlebrook 7H9 broth for 14-16 days, incubated at the same conditions until it reached an OD600

around 0.5. The culture was further diluted with fresh media to an OD600 of 0.3 and continued to  grow under the same condition until it stopped growing and the attained a constant optical density. Primary screening and MIC of library compounds against non-replicating SS18b strain  replicating SS18b strain was carried in triplicates at a single concentration of 16.0 µg/ml in 96-well  U-bottom  plates  (Tarson,  Mumbai,  India).  MIC  of  the  active  compounds  was  determined  against  SS18b strain, 18b strain, and multidrug-resistant (SK-7782 MDR clinical isolate) of M. tuberculosis  using the micro-broth dilution method (Maccari et al. 2002; Wallace et al. 1986).Briefly, in 96-well  U-bottom  plate  compounds  were  two-fold  serially  diluted  in  100µl  volume  in  concentrations  ranging from 16 to 0.06 µg/ml in “Middlebrook 7H9 broth”supplemented with 10% ADC (and 50  μg/ml  streptomycin  for  18b).  1McFarland  (McF)  standard  equivalent  to  1.0  ×  107  CFU/ml  of  bacterial suspension was prepared in a normal saline solution containing 0.5% of Tween 80 and was

further diluted to 1:10 in growth media. A 100 µl volume this inoculums was  added to each well  bringing  the  final  concentration  of  inoculums  to  1.0  ×  106  CFU/ml  (for  SS18b,  100  µl  of  culture  with OD600 of 0.2). Plates were incubated at 37°C for seven days. Presence of growth in the wells  was  assessed  by  Resazurin  Microtitre  Assay  (REMA)  method  (Palomino  et  al  2002).  After  completion of incubation, 15 μl of 0.04% resazurin (Across, Morris Plains, NJ, USA) and 12.5 μl of  20% Tween 80 were added in each well of the plate followed by further incubation for 24 h at 37°C.  The  plates  were  visually  observed  for  the  change  of  color.  MIC  was  defined  as  the  lowest  concentration of the drug that prevented color change from blue to pink due to resazurin reduction.  Rifampicin and isoniazid were used  as standard drugs for assay validation of M. tuberculosis 18b  under replicating and non-replicating state.    2.5. Selection of resistant mutants    The first step mutants of M. tuberculosis H37Rv against 8002-7516 and 3013-0377 were generated  following  method  described  by  Y.  Dong  2002.  Briefly,  a  bacterial  suspension  containing  109  CFU/ml  (100µl)  was  plated  on  Middlebrook  7H10  agar  plates  supplemented  with  10  %  ADC  having two folds increasing MIC concentration of selected compounds upto 16x MIC. Plates were  incubated at 37°C for 4-6 weeks. Frequency of mutation in M. tuberculosis H37Rv in presence of  compounds was calculated. The mutation frequency was calculated by counting the total number of  colonies appearing on compounds containing plate after 28 days of incubation divided by the total  number  of  cfu  plated.  Further,  MIC  of  the  stable  mutants  was  evaluated  to  select  the  resistant  mutant  of  each  compound.  The  MIC  of  these  compounds  was  tested  for  in  vitro  cross  resistance  studies against rifampicin and isoniazid.   2.9. In vitro combination and MBC studies

The potency of the combination of antibiotics in comparison to their individual activities was tested  as described by Eliopoulos and Wennersten, 2002. The comparison is then represented as Fractional  Inhibitory  Concentration  (FIC)  index  value  that  takes  into  account  the  combination  of  antibiotics  producing the greatest change from individual antibiotic’s MIC. In order to quantify the interactions  between the antibiotics being tested (the FIC index), the following equation is used :-  Where FICC is the MIC of each compound in combination/MIC of compound alone and FICD is the  MIC  of  drug  in  combination/MIC  of  drug  alone.  FIC  Index  value  is  used  to  categorize  the  interaction  of  the  two  antibiotics  tested.  Briefly,  in  this  method,  the  efficacy  of  two  selected  compounds  (3013-0377  and  8002-7516)  was  tested  in  combination  with  rifampicin  and  isoniazid  (ranging  from  2-0.007  µg/ml).  Five  compounds  concentrations  ranging  from  4  to  0.25  µg/ml  for  compound  3013-0377  and  from  2  to  0.125  µg/ml  for  compound  8002-7516,  were  tested.  The  checkerboard  method  was  performed.  Followed  by  incubation  of  plates  at  37ºC  for  14  days,  the  MIC of the drug alone and in presence of compound was visually observed and synergy value was  finally  calculated  based  on  the  formula  of  FIC  index.  For  determining  the  Minimum  bactericidal  concentration, a volume of 20 μl from sub MIC concentration were taken and spotted on 7H10 agar  plate supplemented with 10% ADC.  Log10 CFU was counted after 14 days of incubation at 37°C.  The  lowest  concentration  of  antibacterial  agent  that  reduces  the  viability  of  the  initial  bacterial

inoculum by ≥99.9% compared with non-treated control was considered as the MBC of respective  3.1. Primary screening and MIC  Primary screening of 30,000 drugs like compounds from procured ChemDiv library was performed  on non replicating SS18b strain. The MIC of rifampicin and isoniazid, was determined against 18b  and  SS18b.  Rifampicin  was  active  against  18b  and  SS18b,  whereas  isoniazid  showed  very  weak  activity  against  SS18b  cells  (Table  1).  These  findings  were  consistent  with  the  earlier  reported  studies  [21].  Among  470  active  compounds  based  on  primary  screening,  397  compounds  showed  MIC  in  the  range  of  ≥16  µg/mL,  68  compounds  showed  MIC  in  the  range  of  single  digit  i.e  1-8  µg/mL  and  5  compounds  showed  MIC  ≤1  µg/mL  against  SS18b  (Table  2).  Further,  Minimum  inhibitory  concentration  (MIC)  of  these  active  470  compounds  were  also  determined  against  replicating  18b,  and  MDR  M.  tuberculosis  clinical  isolate  using  micro  broth  dilution  method  as  3.2. Being  non- culturable, latent bacteria are unable on solid media because of which current diagnostic techniques  are unable to detect more than 40% of recurrence cases. Recent reports showed the development of  drug resistance acquired by bacteria is not only because of inheritable genetic mechanism but is also  governed  by  its  physiological  state  [14-17,  21,  22].  Streptomycin-starved  (SS18b)  as  a  model  of  choice for dormancy has already been demonstrated by Sala et al. 2010 [18]. Compared to other in  vitro  and  in  vivo  models  used  to  reproduce  latency,  the  SS18b  model  provides  the  research  community  with  a  simple  model  that  mimics  latent  TB  in  animals  with  no  special  equipment  required.
